Customers from Uzbekistan choose tea at an exhibition in Yichang, Central China's Hubei Province on Sunday. Yichang, one of the world's biggest tea-producing areas, harvested 89,700 tons of tea that were sold to more than 30 countries and regions in 2018. More and more of its buyers are from Belt and Road Initiative countries and regions. So far this month, buyers from Uzbekistan, Russia and other markets have signed agreements worth more than $100 million with local tea companies. Photo: IC Chinese scientists design gene-editing tool using light to kill cancer cellsAbsence at PLA maritime parade will prevent US from learning about Chinese Navy: expertsChinese American organization condemns increasing racial profiling in US Actress Liu honored with Hollywood Walk of Fame starDelegation of HUST attends alumni gala in Los AngelesChinese driving Vegas growth